5":"1315","1267":"1267","1299":"1299","1266":"1266","1331":"1331","1265":"1265","about 1267":"about 1267","about 1264":"about 1264","about 1275":"about 1275","about 1331":"about 1331","about 1263":"about 1263","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Bedingfield, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom":"Bedingfield, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom","Bedingfield, Suffolk, England":"Bedingfield, Suffolk, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Bedingfield","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Suffolk and Norfolk): variant of   Beddingfield  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Beddingfield","meanings":["English (Suffolk): habitational name from Bedingfield in Suffolk. The placename is recorded in Domesday Book as <i>Bedingefelda</i>, from the Old English personal name <i>Bēda</i> + the connective particle <i>-ing-</i> ‘associated with, named after’ + <i>feld</i> ‘open country’."]}]},{"name":"Peter","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["form of the name of the best-known of all Christ's apostles, traditionally regarded as the founder of the Christian Church. The name derives, via Latin, from Greek <i>petros</i> ‘stone, rock’. This is used as a translation of the Aramaic byname <i>Cephas</i>, given to the apostle  Simon  son of Jona, to distinguish him from another of the same name (  Simon Zelotes ). ‘When Jesus beheld him, he said, Thou art Simon the son of Jona: thou shalt be called Cephas, which is by interpretation, A stone’ (John 1:42). According to Matthew 16:17–18, Christ says more explicitly, ‘Blessed art thou, Simon Bar-jona … thou art Peter, and upon this rock I will build my church’. The name has been in continuous use since the Middle Ages."],"variants":[]},{"name":"de","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["‘Attainment’."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705190,"age":26,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705191,"age":51,"year":"1315","toYear":"1317","julianDay":2201354,"title":"Famine Strikes Europe","description":"A famine caused by cold winters and wet summers across Europe caused millions to die due to starvation. Desperation from hunger caused high levels of crime, stampedes in bread lines in London, infanticide, and even cannibalism throughout Europe.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705192,"age":64,"year":"1328","julianDay":2206102,"title":"First War of Scottish Independence","description":"The First War of Scottish Independence began after England invaded Scotland in 1296. The Treaty of Edinburgh was signed in 1328 which declared peace between the two kingdoms and brought the war to an end.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Sir Peter de Bedingfield was born about 1264, in Bedingfield, Suffolk, England, his father, Adam de Bedingfield II, was 26 and his mother, Mary de Ossory, was 24. He had at least 2 sons and 1 daughter. He died about 1331, in his hometown, at the age of 69, and was buried in Bedingfield, Suffolk, England."},"et":{"about 1264–about 1331":"umbes 1264–umbes 1331","1264–1331":"1264–1331","1265–Male":"1265–Surnud","1266–Female":"1266–Surnud","1267–Female":"1267–Surnud","1292–Male":"1292–Surnud","1295–Male":"1295–Surnud","1299–1374":"1299–1374","1240–1275":"1240–1275","1242–1267":"1242–1267","1242":"1242","1275":"1275","1374":"1374","1264":"1264","1240":"1240","1295":"1295","1292":"1292","1290":"1290","1315":"1315","1267":"1267","1299":"1299","1266":"1266","1331":"1331","1265":"1265","about 1267":"umbes 1267","about 1264":"umbes 1264","about 1275":"umbes 1275","about 1331":"umbes 1331","about 1263":"umbes 1263","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Bedingfield, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom":"Bedingfield, Suffol